{"title_page": "Andries Treurnicht", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Andries Treurnicht\n| honorific-suffix = MP\n| image = Andries Treurnicht.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = Leader of the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]]\n| term_start = 1982\n| term_end = 1993\n| predecessor = Office created\n| successor = [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]]\n| office2 = Leader of the Opposition\n| term_start2 = 1987\n| term_end2 = 1993\n| predecessor2 = [[Frederik van Zyl Slabbert]]\n| successor2 = [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]]\n| constituency2 =\n| majority2 =\n| office3 = Minister of Public Works, Statistics and Tourism\n| term_start3 = 1979\n| term_end3 = 1980\n| predecessor3 =  \n| successor3 = \n| constituency3 =\n| majority3 =\n| office4 =  Leader of National Party in Transvaal\n| term_start4 = 1978\n| term_end4 = 1982\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| constituency4 =\n| majority4 =\n| office5 = Deputy Minister of Plural Relations and Development\n| term_start5 = 1978\n| term_end5 = 1979\n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| constituency5 =\n| majority5 =\n| office6 = Deputy Minister of Education and Training\n| term_start6 = 1978\n| term_end6 = 1979\n| predecessor6 = \n| successor6 = \n| constituency6 =\n| majority6 =\n| office7 = South African Member of Parliament\n| term_start7 = 1971\n| term_end7 = 1993\n| predecessor7 = \n| successor7 = \n| constituency7 = Waterberg\n| majority7 =\n|office8=Chairman of the [[Afrikaner Broederbond]]\n|term_start8=1972\n|term_end8=1974\n|predecessor8=[[Pieter Johannes Meyer |Meyer, P.J.]]\n|successor8=[[Gerrit Viljoen |Viljoen. G.]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1921|02|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Piketberg]], [[Cape Province]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1993|4|22|1921|02|19}}\n| death_place = [[Cape Town]], Cape Province, [[South Africa]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative]]\n|otherparty = [[National Party (South Africa)|National]] (1971-1982)\n| relations =\n| spouse = Engela Deyer\n| children = 4 daughters<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-andries-treurnicht-1457706.html Obituary: Andries Treurnicht] The Independent. 27 April 1993</ref>\n| residence =\n| occupation =\n| website =\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Andries Petrus Treurnicht''' (19 February 1921 \u2013 22 April 1993) was a [[South Africa]]n politician, Minister of Education during the [[Soweto Riots]] and for a short time leader of the [[Nasionale Party|National Party]] in [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]]. In 1982 he founded and led the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]] of [[South Africa]] whose successes among the white electorate made him [[Leader of the Opposition]] in 1987, a position he retained until his death.\n\nHe was born in [[Piketberg]] ([[Cape Province]]) and began his working life as a journalist, being editor of ''Die Kerkbode'' and ''Hoofstad''. He was a keen sportsman, excelling on the rugby field, playing provincial rugby against the [[All Blacks]] in 1949. After obtaining his [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[Theology]] at the [[University of Stellenbosch]], he completed a Doctorate in Political Philosophy at the [[University of Cape Town]]. He subsequently entered the [[Dutch_Reformed_Church_in_South_Africa_(NGK)|Dutch Reformed Church]] (NG Kerk), serving various congregations as minister for 14 years. He was elected Deputy Chairman of the Cape Synod and later of the General Synod. He married Engela Dreyer on 18 January 1949.\n\n==National Party career==\nIn 1971, he became the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Waterberg District Municipality|Waterberg]]. Newly appointed as Deputy Minister of Education in 1976, his instruction to implement the policy that black students should be taught half in English, half in Afrikaans triggered the [[Soweto Riots]]. In 1978, he was chosen, over the heads of 12 ministers, as Leader of the National Party in the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]], and, in 1979, he became Minister of State for Administration and of Statistics. He was chairman of the Afrikaner Broederbond (AB) from 1972 -1974. He had to leave the AB in 1983, when the newly formed Conservative Party members were not welcome anymore.\n\n==Conservative Party career==\nOn 20 March 1982, he and 22 other MPs quit the National Party to form the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]] to oppose [[P.W. Botha]] and the National Party's limited reforms to [[apartheid]]. The CP's English language programme booklets from 1987-89 stated that the party was established \"to continue the policy of self-determination after the [NP] government had exchanged self-determination\" (something the CP described as an \"infallible policy\"), for power-sharing.<ref>''The Conservative Party has the Solution'', English language party booklet, n/d but early 1989</ref><ref>''The Conservative Party of South Africa - Programme of Principles and Policy'', English language booklet, 1988</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Conservative Party became the official opposition in the  [[House of Assembly of South Africa|House of Assembly]], winning 550,000 votes, displacing the liberal [[Progressive Federal Party]]. Donald Simpson, writing in the South African newspaper, ''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', went as far as to predict that the National Party would lose the next election and that the Conservative Party would become the new government of South Africa.<ref>''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', 24 May 1987</ref>\n\nIn June 1989, accompanied by [[Clive Derby-Lewis]], [[Carl Werth]], and several other Conservative Party officials, Treurnicht made an official visit to London and some other European capitals.  The far-right [[Western Goals Institute]] organized his London visit, and the [[Conservative Monday Club]] held a dinner in his honour, at which at least one British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP, [[Tim Janman]], was present.<ref>''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' Court & Social page, 6 June 1989</ref>\n\nAlready nicknamed \"Doctor No\", in 1992, he led the opposition campaign during the [[1992 South African Referendum|referendum]] called by [[F.W. de Klerk]] to gain white approval for negotiations to end [[apartheid]]. This campaign marked the peak of Conservative support in South Africa, gaining just under one million votes, but the \"No\" vote was defeated 2 to 1 by white voters.<ref>{{cite news|\nurl=https://www.theguardian.com/southafrica/story/0,,1172416,00.html|\ntitle=Sweeping SA vote for reform: Even Afrikaners support De Klerk|\nfirst=David|last=Beresford|\ndate=18 March 1992|\npublisher=The Guardian|\naccessdate=2007-01-12}}</ref>\n\nTreurnicht was the author of no fewer than 16 books, many in the cultural field.\n\nHe died on 22 April 1993, in [[Cape Town]], during a heart operation. His death came shortly after the Conservative Party suffered a major blow with the arrest of senior member  [[Clive Derby-Lewis]] for the murder of [[Chris Hani]]. His former deputy minister, [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]], became the last leader of the Conservative Party.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-28/opinion/op-48_1_south-africa 1991 interview with the Los Angeles Times]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Leaders of the Opposition (South Africa)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treurnicht, Andries}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bergrivier Local Municipality]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa (NGK)]]\n[[Category:National Party (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use South African English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox Politician\n| name = Andries Treurnicht\n| honorific-suffix = MP\n| image = Andries Treurnicht.jpg\n| caption = \n| office = Leader of the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]]\n| term_start = 1982\n| term_end = 1993\n| predecessor = Office created\n| successor = [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]]\n| office2 = Leader of the Opposition\n| term_start2 = 1987\n| term_end2 = 1993\n| predecessor2 = [[Frederik van Zyl Slabbert]]\n| successor2 = [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]]\n| constituency2 =\n| majority2 =\n| office3 = Minister of Public Works, Statistics and Tourism\n| term_start3 = 1979\n| term_end3 = 1980\n| predecessor3 =  \n| successor3 = \n| constituency3 =\n| majority3 =\n| office4 =  Leader of National Party in Transvaal\n| term_start4 = 1978\n| term_end4 = 1982\n| predecessor4 = \n| successor4 = \n| constituency4 =\n| majority4 =\n| office5 = Deputy Minister of Plural Relations and Development\n| term_start5 = 1978\n| term_end5 = 1979\n| predecessor5 = \n| successor5 = \n| constituency5 =\n| majority5 =\n| office6 = Deputy Minister of Education and Training\n| term_start6 = 1978\n| term_end6 = 1979\n| predecessor6 = \n| successor6 = \n| constituency6 =\n| majority6 =\n| office7 = South African Member of Parliament\n| term_start7 = 1971\n| term_end7 = 1993\n| predecessor7 = \n| successor7 = \n| constituency7 = Waterberg\n| majority7 =\n|office8=Chairman of the [[Afrikaner Broederbond]]\n|term_start8=1972\n|term_end8=1974\n|predecessor8=[[Pieter Johannes Meyer |Meyer, P.J.]]\n|successor8=[[Gerrit Viljoen |Viljoen. G.]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1921|02|19}}\n| birth_place = [[Piketberg]], [[Cape Province]], [[Union of South Africa|South Africa]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1993|4|22|1921|02|19}}\n| death_place = [[Cape Town]], Cape Province, [[South Africa]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative]]\n|otherparty = [[National Party (South Africa)|National]] (1971-1982)\n| relations =\n| spouse = Engela Deyer\n| children = 4 daughters<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/obituary-andries-treurnicht-1457706.html Obituary: Andries Treurnicht] The Independent. 27 April 1993</ref>\n| residence =\n| occupation =\n| website =\n}}\n{{Apartheid}}\n'''Andries Petrus Treurnicht''' (19 February 1921 \u2013 22 April 1993) was a [[South Africa]]n politician, Minister of Education during the [[Soweto Riots]] and for a short time leader of the [[Nasionale Party|National Party]] in [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]]. In 1982 he founded and led the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]] of [[South Africa]] whose successes among the white electorate made him [[Leader of the Opposition]] in 1987, a position he retained until his death.\n\nHe was born in [[Piketberg]] ([[Cape Province]]) and began his working life as a journalist, being editor of ''Die Kerkbode'' and ''Hoofstad''. He was a keen sportsman, excelling on the rugby field, playing provincial rugby against the [[All Blacks]] in 1949. After obtaining his [[Master of Arts|MA]] in [[Theology]] at the [[University of Stellenbosch]], he completed a Doctorate in Political Philosophy at the [[University of Cape Town]]. He subsequently entered the [[Dutch Reformed Church]] (NG Kerk), serving various congregations as minister for 14 years. He was elected Deputy Chairman of the Cape Synod and later of the General Synod. He married Engela Dreyer on 18 January 1949.\n\n==National Party career==\nIn 1971, he became the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] [[Member of Parliament|MP]] for [[Waterberg District Municipality|Waterberg]]. Newly appointed as Deputy Minister of Education in 1976, his instruction to implement the policy that black students should be taught half in English, half in Afrikaans triggered the [[Soweto Riots]]. In 1978, he was chosen, over the heads of 12 ministers, as Leader of the National Party in the [[Transvaal Province|Transvaal]], and, in 1979, he became Minister of State for Administration and of Statistics. He was chairman of the Afrikaner Broederbond (AB) from 1972 -1974. He had to leave the AB in 1983, when the newly formed Conservative Party members were not welcome anymore.\n\n==Conservative Party career==\nOn 20 March 1982, he and 22 other MPs quit the National Party to form the [[Conservative Party (South Africa)|Conservative Party]] to oppose [[P.W. Botha]] and the National Party's limited reforms to [[apartheid]]. The CP's English language programme booklets from 1987-89 stated that the party was established \"to continue the policy of self-determination after the [NP] government had exchanged self-determination\" (something the CP described as an \"infallible policy\"), for power-sharing.<ref>''The Conservative Party has the Solution'', English language party booklet, n/d but early 1989</ref><ref>''The Conservative Party of South Africa - Programme of Principles and Policy'', English language booklet, 1988</ref>\n\nIn 1987, the Conservative Party became the official opposition in the  [[House of Assembly of South Africa|House of Assembly]], winning 550,000 votes, displacing the liberal [[Progressive Federal Party]]. Donald Simpson, writing in the South African newspaper, ''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', went as far as to predict that the National Party would lose the next election and that the Conservative Party would become the new government of South Africa.<ref>''[[The Star (South Africa)|The Star]]'', 24 May 1987</ref>\n\nIn June 1989, accompanied by [[Clive Derby-Lewis]], [[Carl Werth]], and several other Conservative Party officials, Treurnicht made an official visit to London and some other European capitals.  The far-right [[Western Goals Institute]] organized his London visit, and the [[Conservative Monday Club]] held a dinner in his honour, at which at least one British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP, [[Tim Janman]], was present.<ref>''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' Court & Social page, 6 June 1989</ref>\n\nAlready nicknamed \"Doctor No\", in 1992, he led the opposition campaign during the [[1992 South African Referendum|referendum]] called by [[F.W. de Klerk]] to gain white approval for negotiations to end [[apartheid]]. This campaign marked the peak of Conservative support in South Africa, gaining just under one million votes, but the \"No\" vote was defeated 2 to 1 by white voters.<ref>{{cite news|\nurl=https://www.theguardian.com/southafrica/story/0,,1172416,00.html|\ntitle=Sweeping SA vote for reform: Even Afrikaners support De Klerk|\nfirst=David|last=Beresford|\ndate=18 March 1992|\npublisher=The Guardian|\naccessdate=2007-01-12}}</ref>\n\nTreurnicht was the author of no fewer than 16 books, many in the cultural field.\n\nHe died on 22 April 1993, in [[Cape Town]], during a heart operation. His death came shortly after the Conservative Party suffered a major blow with the arrest of senior member  [[Clive Derby-Lewis]] for the murder of [[Chris Hani]]. His former deputy minister, [[Ferdinand Hartzenberg]], became the last leader of the Conservative Party.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://articles.latimes.com/1991-07-28/opinion/op-48_1_south-africa 1991 interview with the Los Angeles Times]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Leaders of the Opposition (South Africa)}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Treurnicht, Andries}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Bergrivier Local Municipality]]\n[[Category:Afrikaner people]]\n[[Category:South African people of Dutch descent]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dutch Reformed Church in South Africa (NGK)]]\n[[Category:National Party (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (South Africa) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Assembly of South Africa]]\n[[Category:Stellenbosch University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cape Town alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Dynzmoar", "label": "safe", "comment": "Changed target of Dutch Reformed Church link to article on the South African denomination", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andries_Treurnicht"}
